Who needs limits right? When it comes to data, we sure don’t and thanks to the Wi-Fi on the Go Program we don’t have to worry about data limits, installation fees, long term contracts or being stuck without internet on the road. Nope - for just $50 per month donated to Cullman County Schools, you get UNLIMITED 4G/LTE internet, your own portable hotspot, and the FREEDOM to take your internet with you wherever you go. Yep - that’s right. Stay connected wherever you go & support YOUR schools at the same time. That’s a win-win for sure.

So, have you ordered your hotspot yet? It’s super easy and fast. Just go to http://bit.ly/CullmanCoGIVE, fill out the form, set up your electronic payment and one of these cool devices will be on its way to you too! You have to be a parent or guardian of a student or an employee to get it so have your employee or student id # handy! Questions or comments - send an email to info@leanstreamrp.com. Check it out today! LeanStream #GoAnywhereGoEverywhere

post_text: Dr. Shane Barnette had the honor of meeting with FBI staff in Washington, DC to share with them about the great things going on in Cullman County Schools and the many opportunities we have for our students. A select number of school systems were invited to speak to the FBI employees, as some may relocate to Huntsville and surrounding areas. The FBI announced that it will relocate 1,350 employees from Washington to Huntsville, AL, which could translate to approximately 4,000 jobs.

"Mrs. Whitlock is the epitome of what one would want in an employee. She is loyal, hard-working, and an absolutely unbelievable educator. Her love for Good Hope is on display every day, and that love is only overshadowed by the love for her students. She is giving, kind, and empathetic and when others are having a bad day, she never seems to have one. She is always ready to shoot you a smile when you walk in her room, and her humor and wit helps to keep the students engaged."

Congratulations Mrs. Anita Whitlock! She is one of this month's e5 Exceptional Service Award winners!

post_text:
Parents,
To prevent widespread flu in the schools, please keep in mind times when your child should stay at home:

-Fever‐greater than 100°F, your child should stay home until at least 24 hours after they no longer have a fever. This should be determined without the use of fever‐reducing medicines (any medicine that contains ibuprofen or acetaminophen)

-Vomiting (even once) should stay home at least 24 hours

-Diarrhea should stay home at least 24 hours

-Chills

-General malaise or feelings of fatigue, discomfort, weakness or muscle aches

-Frequent congested (wet) or croup cough

-Lots of nasal congestion with frequent blowing of nose

Ways you can help us prevent the flu and other colds:

-Wash hands frequently.

-Do not touch eyes, nose or mouth.

-Cover mouth and nose when sneezing or coughing.

-Using a paper tissue, throw it away and then wash hands.

-Avoid close contact with people who are sick.

To view additional resources on how you can help prevent the flu please visit: http://ow.ly/PDhF50knn4S

"This morning a phone call was received at West Point Middle School indicating a possible threat to the West Point Schools. Again...everything at this time is safe."
